ative-image-run`) — update\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:55:`fixes-native-image-run-fail`) so review automation can validate the result\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:69:`fails-native-image-build`, or `fails-native-image-run`). Forge claims those\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:98:| **Reachability metadata** | JSON describing reflection, JNI, resource, serialization, and proxy access for a library, consumed by GraalVM `native-image`. |\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:106:| **Post-generation intervention** | The built-in recovery sequence the workflow base class runs when the post-iteration `./gradlew test` still fails during finalization. It is a fixed Codex-then-Pi lane, not a pluggable registry and not selected per strategy: a Codex metadata fix runs first (using the `fix-missing-reachability-metadata` skill, pinned to the run's GraalVM); only if that does not recover does Pi remove the offending failing tests as a last resort. When recovery makes the post-generation test pass, the run reports `SUCCESS_WITH_INTERVENTION_STATUS` and the intervention record (stage, intervention file, analysis) is saved for the run metrics and PR body. The base class runs this lane once per GraalVM test lane (current defaults and `future-defaults-all` on the latest GraalVM, plus current defaults on the GraalVM 25 toolchain). |\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:107:| **Human intervention** | A maintainer follow-up signal applied through the `human-intervention` issue or PR label when Forge has evidence that generated work, repository automation, or library execution semantics require human judgment. It is distinct from post-generation intervention, which is an automated recovery step. The policy is defined in §FS-human-intervention-policy. |\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:108:| **Dynamic access** | Reflection, JNI, resource access, serialization, or proxy use that GraalVM `native-image` cannot determine statically. |\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:158:  full `native-image --version` output into Codex instructions, run Codex with\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:207:  `fix-native-image-run-…`, `not-for-native-image-…`).\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:269:Forge runs the generated tests for the coordinate under the CI native-image\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:278:`META-INF/native-image` test configuration files appear under the generated test\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:296:change, and the human-intervention classification that detects changes outside\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:307:generated tests under the CI native-image mode matrix, and runs Spring AOT smoke\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:315:`human-intervention` and the verification metrics and PR description must list\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:317:§FS-human-intervention-policy.\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:319:### FS-human-intervention-policy: Human intervention policy\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:321:The `human-intervention` label is a maintainer follow-up signal, not a generic\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:326:Valid human-intervention cases are semantic or generation failures inside\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:343:Forge must not use `human-intervention` for failures that are only external or\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:348:appropriate, and left without the `human-intervention` label unless later\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:356:`human-intervention-fixed` PR label means a maintainer has addressed the manual\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:363:`human-intervention` label unless the result also meets one of the policy cases\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:376:`fixes-native-image-run-fail`, and bulk-update review labels each have their\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:380:Review automation must skip PRs already labeled `human-intervention`. That\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:382:continue, per §FS-human-intervention-policy. A PR labeled\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:383:`human-intervention-fixed` is the explicit maintainer signal that manual\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:389:Automated review may add or request the `human-intervention` PR label only when\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:393:infrastructure errors must not be converted into `human-intervention` unless\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:396:(§FS-human-intervention-policy).\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:422:`human-intervention` for these fixable index bucket inconsistencies\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:423:(§FS-human-intervention-policy).\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:440:| `SUCCESS_WITH_INTERVENTION_STATUS` | Tests succeeded after the built-in post-generation recovery modified the working tree (a Codex metadata fix, then Pi removing failing tests as a last resort), and the local CI-equivalent verification (§FS-local-ci-equivalent-verification) passed. The intervention's record is included in the run-metrics and PR description. PR-eligible; distinct from the `human-intervention` label unless §FS-human-intervention-policy separately requires that label. |\n./forge/docs/functional-spec.md:487:| `fails-native-image-run` | `fix_ni_run.py` | native-image run repair (§WF-native-image-run-fix-workflow) |\n./forge/docs/README.md:66:- [workflows/native-image-run-fix.md](workflows/native-image-run-fix.md) — `WF-native-image-run-fix-workflow`.\n./forge/docs/workflows/workflow-drivers.md:86:#### Native Image eligibility (not-for-native-image)\n./forge/docs/workflows/workflow-drivers.md:88:Not every requested artifact is a JVM library that GraalVM `native-image`\n./forge/docs/workflows/workflow-drivers.md:93:   `not-for-native-image`, the driver stops immediately — the artifact is\n./forge/docs/workflows/workflow-drivers.md:105:   `metadata/<group>/<artifact>/index.json` recording `not-for-native-image:\n./forge/docs/workflows/workflow-drivers.md:108:   marker to the dedicated publisher (§GIT-not-for-native-image-publication),\n./forge/docs/workflows/workflow-drivers.md:179:- Resolve the previous and failing library versions, repo